text:section.text:p:
One way to obtain a DynamicData object representing a data sample received by the participant is using the Recorder and RecorderListener classes ( see section
12.1
). Recorder’s get_dynamic_data can be used to construct a DynamicData object for each received sample from the writer. Internally, the CompleteTypeObjects received from discovering th at writer are converted to DynamicTypes and they are then used to construct the DynamicData object s . Once a DynamicData object for a MyStruct sample is constructed, its members can be read as described in the follow ing sections .
Another way to obtain a DynamicData object is from a DynamicDataReader (section
16.7.4.3
) .

ret = data.get_get_uint16_value(my_ushort, 
2
); // Get the value of us_field

ret = data.get_float32_value(my_float, 
3
); // Get the value of f_field

DynamicData objects can be created by the application and populated with data so that they can be used as data samples which are written to a DynamicDataWriter (section
16.7.4.2
) .

DDS::DynamicType_var type = ts_static->get_type();

DDS::DynamicTypeSupport_var ts_dynamic = new DynamicTypeSupport(type);

DDS::ReturnCode_t ret = ts_dynamic->register_type(participant, "");

Now the type support object ts_dynamic can be used in the usual DataWriter/DataReader setup sequence (creating a Topic first, etc.) but the created DataWriters will be DynamicDataWriters (see section 
 16.7.4.2 
) and the created DataReaders will be DynamicDataReaders (see section 
 16.7.4.3 
).
